You are debugging a production issue where a high-performance Spring Boot service is experiencing intermittent `IllegalStateException` or infinite loops. The team recently implemented a custom cache using `ConcurrentHashMap`. Below is the code snippet used to populate the cache:

java
public Value getValue(String key) {
    return cache.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> {
        if (k.startsWith("nested")) {
            return cache.computeIfAbsent("fallback", f -> new Value("default"));
        }
        return fetchFromDB(k);
    });
}

You are investigating a memory leak in a Spring-managed application. A custom LRU (Least Recently Used) cache was implemented by extending `LinkedHashMap`. The cache is declared as a bean and used inside a `@Transactional` service:

java
public class CustomCache<K, V> extends LinkedHashMap<K, V> {
    private final int capacity;
    public CustomCache(int capacity) {
        super(capacity, 0.75f, true);
        this.capacity = capacity;
    }
    @Override
    protected boolean removeEldestEntry(Map.Entry<K, V> eldest) {
        return size() > capacity;
      }
}

Despite the `removeEldestEntry` logic, heap dumps show the map growing indefinitely and holding onto `Entity` objects even after the transaction ends.

You are debugging a production issue where a `List` of processed items is inconsistent after a method call. The code uses Spring's declarative transaction management:

java
@Service
public class ProcessingService {
    @Transactional
    public void processAll(List<String> items) {
        List<String> processed = new ArrayList<>();
        items.forEach(item -> this.internalProcess(item, processed));
        // After this, 'processed' is unexpectedly empty or incomplete
    }

    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void internalProcess(String item, List<String> list) {
        list.add(item.toUpperCase());
    }
}
